We are trying to draw a circle with shaders and use some math functions to calculate the distance from the center of the circle to the coordinates of pixel to draw.

We do something like this:

First attempt (just use distance function)

```
varying vec4 v_fragmentColor;
varying vec2 v_texCoord;

uniform vec2 position;
uniform float lightSize;
uniform float darkness;

void main()
{
    gl_FragColor = vec4(vec3(0,0,0), 1.0);
    
    float distanceValue = distance(gl_FragCoord.xy, position);
    
    if (distanceValue < lightSize) {
        gl_FragColor = vec4(vec3(1,0,0), 1.0);
    }
}
```

This code does a mask with a red circle without opacity from the "position" like the center of the cirlcle. 

This works fine on non retina displays, but when we tried it on retina displays, it works for small values, but when we started to increase them (we noticed it to stop working around 300) it behaves as if for every pixel the condition is true.

Next we do this test:

Second Attempt: Replace distance function

```
varying vec4 v_fragmentColor;
varying vec2 v_texCoord;

uniform vec2 position;
uniform float lightSize;
uniform float darkness;

void main()
{
    gl_FragColor = vec4(vec3(0,0,0), 1.0);
    
    vec2 distanceVector = gl_FragCoord.xy - position.xy;
    float distanceValue = sqrt(pow(distanceVector.x, 2.0) + pow(distanceVector.y, 2.0));
    
    if (distanceValue < lightSize) {
        gl_FragColor = vec4(vec3(1,0,0), 1.0);
    }
}
```

We tried doing the distance calculation by hand and see that when the distanceVector has negative components it was always returning as if the if condition was true (so we got the top left, bottom left, and bottom right quads as red and in the top right corner we got the right behaviour with a quarter red circle and the rest of the quad masked.

